   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3fb1bd3d-df46-402f-a658-6fd0723bc9f7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The iter() Function - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "a8519233-a3c0-4554-bffc-88c4dfdae68e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "What happens when Python performs an iteration over an iterable?\n",
    "\n",
    "The very first thing Python does is call the iter() function on object we want to iterate\n",
    "If the object implements __iter__ method, that method is called and Python uses the returned iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "What happens if the object does not implement the __iter__ method?\n",
    "Is an exception raised?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "355a4904-cabf-40c0-b6ff-227af32a6172",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Sequence Types\n",
    "\n",
    "So how does iterating over a sequence type - that maybe only implemented __getitem__ work?\n",
    "I just said that Python always calls iter() first\n",
    "You'll notice I didn't say Python always calls the __iter__ method\n",
    "It calls iter() function\n",
    "\n",
    "In fact, if obj is an object that only implements __getitem__\n",
    "\n",
    "iter(obj) -> returns an iterator type object"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "ef742034-5c4f-43ac-af2e-243bbbb8b3d8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Some form of magic at work?\n",
    "\n",
    "Not really.\n",
    "Let's think about sequence types and how we can iterate over them\n",
    "Suppose seq is some sequence type that implements __getitem__ (but not __iter__)\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember what happens when we request an index out of bounds from __getitem__ method? -> IndexError\n",
    "\n",
    "index = 0\n",
    "while True:\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        print(seq[index])\n",
    "        index += 1\n",
    "    except IndexError:\n",
    "        break"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0e5c8ebb-43a4-4bb0-aad6-32794555f6ef",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Making an Iterator to iterate over any Sequence\n",
    "\n",
    "class SeqIterator:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, seq):\n",
    "        self.seq = seq\n",
    "        self.index = 0\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __iter__(self):\n",
    "        return self\n",
    "\n",
    "    def __next__:\n",
    "        try:\n",
    "            item = self.seq[self.index]\n",
    "            self.index += 1\n",
    "            return item\n",
    "        exept IndexError:\n",
    "            raise StopIteration()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "094dab98-f311-4d90-a0ef-3b54a2210d45",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Calling iter()\n",
    "\n",
    "So when iter(obj) is called:\n",
    "Python first looks for an __iter__ method\n",
    "-> if it's there use it\n",
    "-> if not look for __getitem__ method\n",
    "    -> if its there create an iterator object and return that\n",
    "    -> if not there raise a TypeError exception (not iterable)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "4558f036-54a9-4edb-9c80-5ac4b86d2d21",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Testing if an object is iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "Sometimes (rarely) you may want to know if object is iterable or not\n",
    "But now you would have to check if they implement\n",
    "\n",
    "__getitem__ or __iter__ and __iter__ returns an iterator\n",
    "\n",
    "Easier Approach:\n",
    "\n",
    "try:\n",
    "    iter(obj)\n",
    "except TypeError:\n",
    "    # not iterable\n",
    "    <code>\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    # is iterable\n",
    "    <code>"
   ]
  },
